Problem Statement¶

Lenders need to know if someone or a company is likely to repay a loan or not before giving it to them. To do this, we want to create a Machine Learning model that can predict this with a high level of accuracy. It's like a yes-or-no question: Will the borrower pay back the loan or not?

#https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mirzahasnine/loan-data-set

#note before running the notebook on Collab please load the train and test datasets 
# https://plainenglish.io/blog/how-can-we-upload-data-to-google-colab-ef31394b004a

Data Description

The dataset has 12 columns. It has 11 features to be used predicting the label which is Status columns in the dataset.

  • 1-pandas for data analysis.

  • 3-Matplotlib / seaborn for plotting or data visualization.
  • 4-Scikit-Learn for machine learning modelling and evaluation.

count = len(df_train['Status'])
count_y = df_train['Status'].value_counts()['Y']
count_n = df_train['Status'].value_counts()['N']

print('Y:', count_y, f'{(count_y / count) * 100:.2f}%')
print('N:', count_n, f'{(count_n / count) * 100:.2f}%')
#The code generates a summary of the 'Status' column in the DataFrame df_train. The summary includes the following information:
# Total count: It calculates the total number of records in the 'Status' column and assigns it to the variable count.
# Count and percentage of 'Y': It counts the occurrences of 'Y' in the 'Status' column and assigns the count to the variable count_y. It then calculates the percentage of 'Y' by dividing count_y by the total count (count), multiplying by 100, and formatting the result with two decimal places. This information is printed as "Y: count_y percentage_Y%" using the print statement.
# Count and percentage of 'N': It counts the occurrences of 'N' in the 'Status' column and assigns the count to the variable count_n. It calculates the percentage of 'N' by dividing count_n by the total count (count), multiplying by 100, and formatting the result with two decimal places. This information is printed as "N: count_n percentage_N%" using the print statement.
# The summary provides insights into the distribution of 'Y' and 'N' values in the 'Status' column, displaying their respective counts and percentages

Pie chart Plotting
In [21]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(15, 10))
#creates a figure with one row and four columns of subplots, resulting in four subplots arranged horizontally. 
#The figsize parameter specifies the size of the figure.
features = ['Gender', 'Education', 'Self_Employed', 'Married','Area']
# list contains the names of the categorical features: 'Gender', 'Education', 'Self_Employed', and 'Married'. 
#These features will be displayed as pie charts in the subplots.

for i, feature in enumerate(features):
#The for loop iterates over each element (feature) in the features list, along with an index (i) indicating the position of the feature in the list.
    pie_data = df_train[feature].value_counts() #calculates the frequency of each unique value in the column.
    pie_data.plot.pie(ax=ax[i], autopct='%1.1f%%')
    ax[i].set_ylabel('') #removes the y-axis label for the current subplot.
    ax[i].set_title(feature.capitalize(), fontweight='bold')# sets the title for the current subplot, capitalizing the feature name and making the title bold.

plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)#adjusts the vertical spacing between subplots to provide some spacing.
plt.show()

#The code creates a figure with four subplots, each showing a pie chart for a specific categorical feature.
#It iterates over the features, generates the value counts, plots the pie chart, sets titles and labels, and displays the figure.
Results and observation
  • In the dataset majority of gender Male with 81.8% while females are 18.2%.
  • The majority of people graduated from their standard education.
  • The majority of people are NOT self-employed which means that Majority of the applicants are working as employee. Self employeed applicants are minority.
  • The majority of applicants are married having 65.3% .
  • The number of applicants who live in Urban and Rural areas are similar to each other.
  • However, the majority live in Semiurban areas is 37.9%

Data Preprocessing
  • Handling Null Values:

Implementing appropriate strategies to handle missing values in your dataset, such as filling them with a specific value, using statistical measures like mean or median, or employing advanced imputation techniques.

  • Handle Duplicates:

Identifying and remove any duplicate records from your dataset to avoid redundancy and potential bias in your analysis.

  • Encode Categorical Features:

Converting categorical variables into numerical representations suitable for machine learning algorithms. Common encoding techniques include one-hot encoding, label encoding, or ordinal encoding.

  • Remove Outliers:

Detecting and remove outliers from your dataset. Outliers can adversely impact the model's performance by distorting the distribution and influencing the decision boundaries. Various statistical methods or domain knowledge can be used to identify outliers.

  • Spliting the Dataset:

Spliting the dataset into training and testing sets before performing any further steps. This separation ensures that your model's performance evaluation is done on unseen data, preventing any data leakage and providing a more accurate assessment of its generalization.

  • Scaling Numerical Features:

Applying feature scaling techniques to normalize the numerical variables in your dataset. Common scaling methods include standardization (subtracting the mean and dividing by the standard deviation) or normalization (scaling values between a specified range, such as 0 and 1). Note that scaling should be performed separately on the training and testing sets.

In [194]:
df_train['Credit_History'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df_test['Credit_History'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
df_val['Credit_History'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

df_train['Self_Employed'].fillna('No', inplace=True)
df_test['Self_Employed'].fillna('No', inplace=True)
df_val['Self_Employed'].fillna('No', inplace=True)

df_train['Gender'].fillna('Male', inplace=True)
df_test['Gender'].fillna('Male', inplace=True)
df_val['Gender'].fillna('Male', inplace=True)

df_train['Dependents'].fillna('0', inplace=True)
df_test['Dependents'].fillna('0', inplace=True)
df_val['Dependents'].fillna('0', inplace=True)

df_train['Loan_Amount'].fillna(df_train['Loan_Amount'].mean(), inplace=True)
# filling missing values using train average 
df_test['Loan_Amount'].fillna(df_train['Loan_Amount'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_val['Loan_Amount'].fillna(df_train['Loan_Amount'].mean(), inplace=True)

df_train['Term'].fillna(df_train['Term'].mean(), inplace=True)
# filling missing values using train average
df_test['Term'].fillna(df_train['Term'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_val['Term'].fillna(df_train['Term'].mean(), inplace=True)

df_train['Married'].fillna('Yes', inplace=True)
df_test['Married'].fillna('Yes', inplace=True)
df_val['Married'].fillna('Yes', inplace=True)

# We can't drop the rows with missing values from the test set as we need to make predictions on it and submit it on Kaggle.
# So we will fill the missing values in the test set with the mode of the respective columns in the train set.
df_test = df_test.fillna(df_train.mode().iloc[0]).reset_index(drop=True)

Outliers Removal

There are multiple ways to remove outliers from a dataset. Here are a few common approaches: The detail explanation can be found in below video https://youtu.be/XzEXB12N1xs

  • 1- Z-Score Method: Calculate the z-score for each data point, which represents how many standard deviations it is away from the mean. Define a threshold (e.g., z-score > 3 or z-score < -3) and remove the data points that exceed this threshold.

  • 2- IQR (Interquartile Range) Method: Calculate the IQR, which is the range between the 25th and 75th percentiles of the data. Define a threshold (e.g., values outside 1.5 times the IQR) and remove the data points that fall outside this range.

  • 3-Visual Inspection: Create box plots, histograms, or scatter plots to visualize the data distribution. Identify any data points that appear to be significantly distant from the majority of the data and remove them based on domain knowledge or data-specific criteria.

  • 4-Domain Knowledge: Apply domain-specific rules or knowledge to identify and remove outliers. For example, if we know the valid range of values for a particular feature, you can remove any data points that fall outside that range.

It's important to note that the choice of outlier removal method depends on your dataset, the specific problem domain, and the characteristics of the outliers you are dealing with. It's advisable to exercise caution and consider the implications of removing outliers, as it can potentially affect the overall distribution and statistical properties of the data.

1:Z-Score

Z-scores can determine how odd observation is when your data follow a normal distribution. Z-scores are the number of standard deviations above and below the mean decrease for each value. For example, a Z-score of 2 indicates that the observation is two standard deviations above the mean, while a Z-score of -2 indicates two standard deviations below the mean. The Z score of zero represents a value equal to the mean. To calculate the Z-score for the observation, take the original measurement, subtract the mean, and divide by the standard deviation. Mathematically, the formula for this process is: z = (X – μ) / σ

The further an observer's Z-score is from zero, the more extravagant they are. The standard cut-off value for finding outliers is Z degrees +/- 3 or greater than zero. The probability distribution below shows the distribution of Z scores in a standard normal distribution. Z degrees above +/- 3 are so severe that you can barely see the shading below the curve.

#Simplified code 
# specify the columns to remove outliers from dataframe
column_names = ['Applicant_Income', 'Coapplicant_Income', 'Loan_Amount','Term']

# remove outliers for each selected column using the IQR method
for column_name in column_names:
    Q1 = df_train[column_name].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df_train[column_name].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    df_train = df_train[~((df_train[column_name] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df_train[column_name] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)))]

https://thatascience.com/learn-machine-learning/label-encoding/

In [215]:
from sklearn import preprocessing

# Loop over each column in the DataFrame where dtype is 'object'
for col in df_train.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns:
    
    # Initialize a LabelEncoder object
    label_encoder = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
    
    # Fit the encoder to the unique values in the column
    label_encoder.fit(df_train[col].unique())
    
    # Transform the column using the encoder
    df_train[col] = label_encoder.transform(df_train[col])
    if col != 'Status':
        # Transform the column using the encoder in the test set
        df_test[col] = label_encoder.transform(df_test[col])
    # Transform the column using the encoder in the validation set
    df_val[col] = label_encoder.transform(df_val[col])
    
    # Print the column name and the unique encoded values
    print(f"{col}: {df_train[col].unique()}")

Decision Tree with Hyperparameter Tuning

In machine learning, a model has two types of parameters: Hyperparameters and learned parameters. The learned parameters are updated during the training process, while the hyperparameters are set before the training begins.

Hyperparameters control the model’s behavior, and their values are usually set based on domain knowledge or heuristics. https://datasciencedojo.com/blog/hyperparameter-tuning/

In [225]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier()
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 3, 4],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 3, 4]
}

# Perform a grid search with cross-validation to find the best hyperparameters
grid_search = GridSearchCV(dtree, param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Print the best hyperparameters
print(grid_search.best_params_)
